The purpose of a rehabilitation project is:
to bring a building to a decent, safe, and sanitary condition in accordance with applicable codes and standards, including those for construction, health, safety, fire, and occupancy;
to maintain the building in that condition;
to make the building more useful and attractive;
to conform the building to the appropriate minimum livability code;
to acquire a building containing more than four dwelling units for the purposes set forth in items (1) through (4) of this subsection;
to provide, under applicable special loan programs:
lead paint abatement;
indoor plumbing; or
shared, accessory, or sheltered housing;
in the case of a loan to an elderly household or a disabled homeowner, to modify or improve a dwelling to make it more accessible or functional for the occupants, if the building is, or after improvements will be, structurally sound and free of health and safety hazards; or
to provide, under applicable special loan pilot programs, radon abatement or asbestos abatement.
